        COLLABORATE_ON_RESEARCH_TITLE: "Collaborate on Research",
        COLLABORATE_ON_RESEARCH_DESC: "<p>We collaborate with academic researchers, respected authors, and other thought leaders to conduct original research on the psychology of personality.</p><p>Historically, a major limitation for psychometric researchers has been access to good data sets. Many researchers have to settle for surveying a few hundred students studying psychology or related topics at their university. These samples are often too small for strong statistical validity, and are biased as they often use self-selected populations with specific demographics and interests.</p><p><b>We are on a mission to change this</b> by making large survey samples with less selection bias available to researchers.</p><h3>How it Works</h3><p>Our personality test uses 120 questions that assess Big Five traits with six facets within each of the Big Five, a total of 30 facets. Our questionnaire uses the public domain 120 questions developed by John Johnson, Professor Emeritus of Psychology, Pennsylvania State University, presented in his paper <a href='https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0092656614000506?via%3Dihub' target=\"_blank\">\"Measuring thirty facets of the Five Factor Model with a 120-item public domain inventory: Development of the IPIP-NEO-120\"</a> and shared on The <a href='https://ipip.ori.org/30FacetNEO-PI-RItems.htm' target=\"_blank\">International Personality Item Pool (IPIP)</a> site.</p><p>To conduct research, after visitors to our site have completed Johnson's 120-question Big Five survey, we present them with additional, optional questions. These questions are generally single sentences or short paragraphs that the user may agree or disagree with on a <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Likert_scale' target=\"_blank\">Likert scale</a> of -3 to +3, for example, \"I have a written plan for my life\". For each of these additional questions, we typically collect 1,000 responses. The exact number of responses can be adjusted to ensure statistical validity depending on the requirements of the current research project.</p><p>We also collect age, gender, geographic location and language preference (currently English and Spanish are supported).</p><p>This allows us to collect large volumes of survey data for Big Five traits (and thirty facets), demographic data and responses to the questions we are currently researching. At the time of writing (October 7, 2020), we have surveyed 167,322 people and received 16,993,597 responses to 9,394 research questions.</p><p><b>These additional questions are how we are able to support ongoing research.</b> As we can add any questions we like to the additional questions, we can support any legitimate and ethical research into the relationships between Big Five traits, demographics and other factors ranging from lifestyle, family and romantic relationships, career path, life outcomes, etc.</p><p>We are eager to collaborate with academic researchers, respected authors, and other thought leaders to conduct original research together.</p><p>If your research interest is a good fit, we would:</p><ol className=\"collaborate_on_reasearch\"><li>Work with you to write the additional questions that we would ask our users, and establish the number of responses needed for statistical validity. We have the capability to test large numbers of questions quickly.</li><li>Collect the required number of responses to each question from users around the world.</li><li>Analyze the results with you and publish a paper with you about the findings. This analysis and the process of writing the paper we can do with you if you are an academic researcher, or on your behalf if you are less familiar with psychometrics and statistical analysis. We would generally publish a summary of the research results on our blog, and encourage you to publish the results elsewhere.</li></ol><p><b>Collaborating with us on research has no cost.</b> We are a research-first company, and research collaboration is both part of our mission and a way to give back.</p><p>While we cannot say yes to everyone who requests to do research with us, we do consider and reply to each request.</p><p>If you are interested in collaborating on research, please contact <a href='mailto:research@interpersonality.com'>research@interpersonality.com</a>.</p>",

